[ma] Cases 22CF10, 22CF11 called at 3:19 PM 
Defendant Aubrey A. Mueller in court with Attorney Jeffrey Jacob De La Rosa.   ADA Michael Witt appears for the State of Wisconsin.

Constitutional rights reviewed; maximum penalties recited; plea of "  NO CONTEST " entered to charge in Case 22CF10; factual basis stipulated; the Court accepts the plea, finds Defendant guilty, and orders Judgment of Conviction entered.

On Motion of the State, the Court reads in and dismisses: Case 22CF11

The Court sentences the Defendant to  39 months Imprisonment, consisting of 21 months Initial Confinement and 18 months Extended Supervision, consecutive to any other sentence.

The Court finds that the Defendant is eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program "Boot Camp".
The Court finds that the Defendant is eligible for the Substance Abuse Program.
The Court gives   0  days credit for time already served.

The Court STAYS this sentence and places Ms. Mueller on probation for 4 years, with conditions:
--to undergo AODA assessment and follow through with recommended treatment per Agent
--to undergo any other assessment, treatment, or counseling per Agent
--random drug and/or alcohol screening
--to obtain/maintain employment and/or education program per Agent
--no possession of controlled substances without a valid prescription
--take any and all prescription medications only as prescribed by treating physician
--no contact with any know drug offender except for treatment or as deemed appropriate per Agent
--if permitted to travel out of State, no possession or use of marijuana(THC) in states where it is legal. No legal CBD products or other legal cannabis derivatives without express written permission of agent
--to comply with DNA sample provision 

Separate from the conditions of Probation, the Court orders payment of costs, fees and surcharges to include $50 drug testing fees and $250 buy money reimbursment through the Clerk of Courts Office. [Clerk calculates this total to be:$818] The Court grants the Defendant sixty days to either pay the amount in full or to establish a payment plan with the Clerk of Courts Office.  Non-payment will result in  16 days in Jail with Huber privileges, consecutive.
